        </div></div></gfg-carousel><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><i><em class=
=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">Bayes' Theorem helps us update probabilitie=
s based on prior knowledge and new evidence. In this case, knowing that the=
 pet is quiet (new information), we can use Bayes' Theorem to calculate the=
 updated probability of the pet being a cat or a dog, based on how likely e=
ach animal is to be quiet.</em></i></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"bayes-theorem=
-and-conditional-probability" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Bayes Th=
eorem and Conditional Probability</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"=
text-align: justify;"><span>Bayes' theorem (also known as the Bayes Rule or=
 Bayes Law) is used to determine the conditional probability of event A whe=
n event B has already occurred.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-alig=
n: justify;"><span>The general statement of Bayes=E2=80=99 theorem is =E2=
=80=9CThe </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/conditional=
-probability/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>conditional probabi=
lity </span></a><span>of an event A, given the occurrence of another event =
B, is equal to the product of the probability of B, given A, and the probab=
ility of A divided by the probability of event B.</span><b><strong>=E2=80=
=9D</strong></b><span>&nbsp;i.e.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=
=3D"text-align: left;"><b><strong>For example,</strong></b><span>&nbsp;if w=
e want to find the probability that a white marble drawn at random came fro=
m the first bag, given that a white marble has already been drawn, and&nbsp=
;there are three bags each containing some white and black marbles, then we=
 can use Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem.</span></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"also-chec=
k" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Also Check</strong></b></h3><blockq=
uote><p dir=3D"ltr"><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/bayess-t=
heorem-for-conditional-probability/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><b>=
<strong>Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem for Conditional Probability</strong></b></a>=
</p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"bayes-theorem-formula" style=3D"text-align:left"=
><b><strong>Bayes Theorem Formula</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"=
text-align: justify;"><span>For any two events A and B, </span><b><strong>B=
ayes's</strong></b><span> formula for the Bayes theorem is given by:</span>=
</p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop_InContent_ATF_728x280" style=3D"text-align: c=
enter; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https:/=
/media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20251206130704617861/p_a_b_.web=
p" alt=3D"p_a_b_" width=3D"635" height=3D"234"><figcaption>Formula for the =
Bayes theorem</figcaption></figure><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Where,</span></p><u=
l><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>P(A)</strong></b><span> and </span><b><strong>=
P(B)</strong></b><span> are the probabilities of events A and B; also, P(B)=
 is never equal to zero.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><strong>P(A|B)</stro=
ng></b><span> is the probability of event A when event B happens,</span></l=
i><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>P(B|A)</strong></b><span> is the probability o=
f event B when A happens.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"bayes-theorem-statement=
" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Bayes Theorem Statement</strong></b>=
</h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><b><strong>Bayes' Theore=
m for n sets of events is defined as,</strong></b></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=
=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Let E</span><sub><span>1</span></sub><span>=
, E</span><sub><span>2</span></sub><span>,=E2=80=A6, E</span><sub><span>n</=
